After redeploying, submit the snapshot again. If you do not see:

```text
Calling Ping create API for userId=...
```

then the snapshot flow is not reaching this method.

## 2. Put the Ping call in the snapshot creation branch

Find the method handling the snapshot request. It likely contains logic similar to:

```java
Optional<UserEntity> existingUser =
        userRepository.findByUserId(userId);
```

The Ping call must be added to the branch that creates a new `UserEntity`.

```java
@Transactional
public UserEntity processSnapshot(UserSnapshot snapshot) {
    Optional<UserEntity> existingUser =
            userRepository.findByUserId(
                    snapshot.getSource().getGpsGroupNumber()
            );

    if (existingUser.isPresent()) {
        return updateExistingUser(
                existingUser.get(),
                snapshot
        );
    }

    UserEntity newUser = mapToUserEntity(snapshot);
    UserEntity savedUser = userRepository.save(newUser);

    log.info(
            "New partner-repository user created, calling Ping. userId={}",
            savedUser.getUserId()
    );

    pingUserClient.createUser(savedUser);

    savedUser.setPingSyncStatus("SUCCESS");
    savedUser.setPingLastSyncedAt(Instant.now());
    savedUser.setPingLastError(null);

    return userRepository.save(savedUser);
}
```

The important part is:

```java
pingUserClient.createUser(savedUser);
```

inside the actual snapshot flow.

## 3. Check whether the user already exists

You sent the snapshot twice. The logs show two successful requests:

```text
15:31:34 POST ... 200 OK
15:32:26 POST ... 200 OK
```

If the first request already created the user, the second request may follow the update branch, not the create branch.

Add logging around the existence check:

```java
